Vladimir Putin and the risk of a third world war
San Francisco – February 24, The Russian invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a third world war that could potentially destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a long meeting on February 4 – that day marked the beginning of China's lunar New Year celebration and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
After the meeting, the two sides released a 5000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and definitely requires detailed negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seems to have entrusted Putin with launching an invasion and waging war in Ukraine.
He believes that confirming himself as China's lifelong ruler in the second half of the year is just a formality, and he's confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned his own scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin started to implement his lifelong dream in an unbelievable, savage manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin felt that if he wanted to leave a deep mark in Russian history, it would be now or never.
But his views on Russia's influence in the world are distorted.
He seems to think that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can blindly follow.
This system is in stark contrast to a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the "soul" of the Russian people who are emotionally inclined to be moody and sentimental.
In my childhood, I had many contacts with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I called my political philanthropic career.
Initially, I established a foundation in my homeland of Hungary, and then actively participated in contributing to the activities that led to the collapse of the Soviet Empire.
The collapse had already begun when Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985.
I also founded a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, I even established a foundation before it became an independent nation.
I had also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner to be allowed to set up a foundation (I closed down the foundation in 1989, shortly after the Tiananmen Square massacre occurred).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise and fully understand his cold-blooded personality.
He reduced Chechnya's capital city, Grozny, to rubble, and now threatens to do the same to Ukraine's capital, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever KGB agent, but he seems to have changed lately.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed idea.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian people who speak Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in reality, they are no different from the people who speak Ukrainian.
Against the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still performed an incredible brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and Ukrainians were misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kiev is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not entirely without historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have known more clearly about the facts.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the 2014 Euromaidan protests.
2014 events made him very angry.
But when he received the order to attack his Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The corruption deeply rooted at the same time also played an important role in this miserable performance.
But Putin not only did not blame himself, but it seemed like he had gone mad instead.
He has decided to punish Ukraine, which opposes him, and his actions seem to be unconstrained in any way.
He has thrown the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were targeted, and the power grid that supplies electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
There are as many as 4 million people without water and food in the besieged Mariupol in recent weeks.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine at the same time as they are trying to buy Russian MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has achieved a miracle in strengthening European determination and unity.
At the same time, it seems that Xi has realized that Putin has strayed.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi firmly stated that the friendship between China and Russia remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping activities.
He hopes to maintain the maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
Whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes is fundamentally impossible to determine.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be driven out before they destroy our civilization.
